		  the VLT-FLAMES Tarantula Survey (VFTS), we aim to establish
		  the{\textbackslash}n(projected) rotational velocity
		  distribution for a sample of 216{\textbackslash}npresumably
		  single O-type stars in 30 Dor. The sample is large enough
		  to{\textbackslash}nobtain statistically significant
		  information and to search for{\textbackslash}nvariations
		  among subpopulations - in terms of spectral type,
		  luminosity{\textbackslash}nclass, and spatial location - in
		  the field of view. {$<$}BR /{$>$} Methods:
		  We{\textbackslash}nmeasured projected rotational
		  velocities, \{\${$\nu\$$}\}\$\_\{e\}\$sini, by
		  means{\textbackslash}nof a Fourier transform method and a
		  profile fitting method applied to a{\textbackslash}nset of
		  isolated spectral lines. We also used an iterative
		  deconvolution{\textbackslash}nprocedure to infer the
		  probability density, P(\{\${$\nu\$$}\}\$\_\{e\}\$), of
		  the{\textbackslash}nequatorial rotational velocity,
		  \{\${$\nu\$$}\}\$\_\{e\}\$. {$<$}BR /{$>$} Results:
		  The{\textbackslash}ndistribution of
		  \{\${$\nu\$$}\}\$\_\{e\}\$sini shows a two-component
		  structure: a{\textbackslash}npeak around 80
		  kms\$\^{}\{-1\}\$ and a high-velocity tail extending up
		  to{\textbackslash}n{\textasciitilde}600 kms\$\^{}\{-1\}\$.
		  This structure is also present in the
		  inferred{\textbackslash}ndistribution
		  P(\{\${$\nu\$$}\}\$\_\{e\}\$) with around 80\% of the
		  sample having 0{\textbackslash}n\{{\textbackslash}lt\}
		  \{\${$\nu\$$}\}\$\_\{e\}\$ \{{\textbackslash}le\} 300
		  kms\$\^{}\{-1\}\$ and the other
		  20\%{\textbackslash}ndistributed in the high-velocity
		  region. The presence of the{\textbackslash}nlow-velocity
		  peak is consistent with what has been found in
		  other{\textbackslash}nstudies for late O- and early B-type
		  stars. {$<$}BR /{$>$} Conclusions: Most
		  of{\textbackslash}nthe stars in our sample rotate with a
		  rate less than 20\% of their{\textbackslash}nbreak-up
		  velocity. For the bulk of the sample, mass loss in a
		  stellar{\textbackslash}nwind and/or envelope expansion is
		  not efficient enough to significantly{\textbackslash}nspin
		  down these stars within the first few Myr of evolution.
		  If{\textbackslash}nmassive-star formation results in stars
		  rotating at birth with a large{\textbackslash}nportion of
		  their break-up velocities, an alternative braking
		  mechanism,{\textbackslash}npossibly magnetic fields, is
		  thus required to explain the
		  present-day{\textbackslash}nrotational properties of the
		  O-type stars in 30 Dor. The presence of
		  a{\textbackslash}nsizeable population of fast rotators is
		  compatible with recent{\textbackslash}npopulation synthesis
		  computations that investigate the influence
		  of{\textbackslash}nbinary evolution on the rotation rate of
		  massive stars. Even though we{\textbackslash}nhave excluded
		  stars that show significant radial velocity
		  variations,{\textbackslash}nour sample may have remained
		  contaminated by post-interaction
		  binary{\textbackslash}nproducts. That the high-velocity
		  tail may be populated primarily
		  (and{\textbackslash}nperhaps exclusively) by post-binary
		  interaction products has
		  important{\textbackslash}nimplications for the evolutionary
		  origin of systems that produce{\textbackslash}ngamma-ray
		  bursts.{\textbackslash}n{\textbackslash}nBased on
		  observations collected at the European Southern
		  Observatory{\textbackslash}nunder program ID
